Jamaica’s ancient history covered the period between 1,500B.C. (incidentally the very first date found on stone using the Mayan method of writing), and 1500 A.D. The early inhabitation of the island dates back to this time as evidenced by the discovery of early pottery, artifacts and the many stone monuments, the jars and burial sites around the island. It became clear by the 13th and 14th centuries that the Taino Indians were the first inhabitants of the island. This is due to artifacts found in various locations in the island. Taino Indians were considered to be an agricultural people cultivating farmlands improving various lands for farming. They used many stones for agricultural purposes.
